{
  "texts": [
    "The second fact appears implicitly and, sometimes, explicitly in the discussion over potential and actual bias in the design, development and deployment of AI.",
    "Within AI ethics and neuroethics the first and second aspects have been addressed in several articles and books [2,18,31,39,[68][69][70][71][72][73].",
    "Here we focus on the third which has received less attention.What does it mean to say that cultural factors shape interpretations, framings, and conceptualization?",
    "Consider the brain: people's understanding of what it is and does has morphed throughout history, shaped by specific historical and cultural contexts.",
    "Importantly, available technologies have played an important role in shaping the metaphors that have been used to describe and give meaning to it (e.g., in the past, the brain was explained referring to the telegraph or telephone, the most advanced technologies then available, while in more recent time we have tended to describe the brain as a computer) [17]."
  ]
}